You didn=E2=80=99t do all that research. You didn=E2=80=99t run those A/B t=
ests. The =E2=80=9Cclient=E2=80=9D was actually a practice project from a b=
ootcamp. The =E2=80=9C20% increase in conversion=E2=80=9D is a number you m=
ade up because every case study needs metrics. And here=E2=80=99s the thing=
: hiring managers know. They=E2=80=99ve seen hundreds of portfolios and the=
y can smell BS instantly. This issue breaks down why portfolio dishonesty h=
appens, how it backfires, and how to present your actual work honestly in a=
 way that still gets you hired.
In this issue:
The lies hiring managers spot immediately
Why fabricating results is worse than having no results
How to present real work (even when it=E2=80=99s messy)
What to do when you genuinely don=E2=80=99t have metrics
The honesty that actually impresses interviewers
=F0=9F=93=A6 Resource Corner
The lies hiring managers spot immediately
Let=E2=80=99s be direct about what=E2=80=99s happening. Designers, especial=
ly junior ones, feel pressure to have impressive portfolios. So they embell=
ish. They exaggerate. Sometimes they straight-up invent things. And hiring =
managers can tell.
Here are the red flags that scream =E2=80=9Cthis didn=E2=80=99t really happ=
en=E2=80=9D:
=F0=9F=9A=A9 Every project has perfect, round metrics =E2=80=9CIncreased co=
nversion by 25%.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CReduced bounce rate by 30%.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9CImproved user satisfaction by 40%.=E2=80=9D These numbers are suspici=
ously clean. Real metrics are messy: 23.7%, 18%, 34.2%. When every project =
ends in a multiple of 5 or 10, it looks made up.
=F0=9F=9A=A9 The process is too perfect Real design is messy. You interview=
 the wrong people. Stakeholders change their minds. Developers push back on=
 your design. Timeline gets cut. But portfolio case studies show this perfe=
ct linear process: research =E2=86=92 insights =E2=86=92 wireframes =E2=86=
=92 testing =E2=86=92 shipping =E2=86=92 success. That=E2=80=99s fiction.
=F0=9F=9A=A9 No mention of constraints, tradeoffs, or failures Every real p=
roject has constraints. Budget. Timeline. Technical limitations. Stakeholde=
r opinions. But portfolio projects never mention them. Every decision was o=
ptimal. Nothing was compromised. That=E2=80=99s not how work happens.
=F0=9F=9A=A9 =E2=80=9CI did everything=E2=80=9D (on a team project) =E2=80=
=9CI conducted the research, designed the solution, and shipped the feature=
=2E=E2=80=9D If this was a real company wi=
th a real team, where was the PM? T=
he researchers? The other designers? Taking sole credit for collaborative w=
ork is an instant credibility killer.
=F0=9F=9A=A9 The timeline doesn=E2=80=99t make sense =E2=80=9CI conducted 1=
5 user interviews, analyzed the data, created wireframes, built high-fideli=
ty mockups, ran usability tests, and launched in 2 weeks.=E2=80=9D No, you =
didn=E2=80=99t. That=E2=80=99s 6-8 weeks minimum. Compressed timelines reve=
al that the story is fabricated.
=F0=9F=9A=A9 Vague or missing company/client details =E2=80=9CA fintech sta=
rtup=E2=80=9D instead of naming the company. =E2=80=9CAn e-commerce client=
=E2=80=9D without specifics. If it was real work, you=E2=80=99d name them (=
or explain the NDA). Vagueness suggests it=E2=80=99s a practice project you=
=E2=80=99re pretending was real.
=F0=9F=9A=A9 The problems are generic, the solutions are trendy =E2=80=9CUs=
ers found the checkout confusing, so I simplified it=E2=80=9D describes eve=
ry checkout redesign ever. Real projects have specific, messy problems. Gen=
eric problems suggest you=E2=80=99re retrofitting a solution you saw elsewh=
ere.
Why this matters: Hiring managers aren=E2=80=99t trying to catch you lying.=
 But when they spot inconsistencies, they start questioning everything in y=
our portfolio. One fabricated detail ruins your credibility on legitimate w=
ork.
Join Don Norman at UXCON26
Co-Founder, Nielsen Norman Group =C2=B7 Former VP of Advanced Technology, A=
pple =C2=B7 Founder, Design Lab at UC San Diego Headlining Keynote
Don Norman is famous for doors that are confusing to open. They are called =
Norman Doors. If you have ever pushed a door that should be pulled, you hav=
e lived inside one of his ideas.
That is what Don Norman does. He makes you see the world differently.
He coined the term =E2=80=9Cuser experience.=E2=80=9D He wrote The Design o=
f Everyday Things, the book on virtually every designer=E2=80=99s shelf, no=
w in its revised edition and still as essential as the day it was published=
=2E He helped found the world=E2=80=99s fi=
rst Department of Cognitive Science=
 at UC San Diego. He became Vice President of Advanced Technology at Apple.=
 He co-founded the Nielsen Norman Group, the firm that shaped how the entir=
e industry thinks about human-centered design. He has published 21 books tr=
anslated into over 20 languages. He holds three honorary degrees and is a m=
ember of the National Academy of Engineering.
Hearing Don Norman speak in 2026 is not a checkbox on a conference list. It=
 is a genuine once-in-a-career opportunity.
Why fabricating results is worse than having no results
The instinct makes sense: every article about portfolios says =E2=80=9Cshow=
 impact=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cinclude metrics.=E2=80=9D So if you don=E2=80=
=99t have metrics, you feel like you need to invent them. But that=E2=80=99=
s backwards.
Here=E2=80=99s what actually happens when you fake results:
=E2=9D=8C You can=E2=80=99t defend them in interviews =E2=80=9CTell me more=
 about that 30% conversion increase. What were you measuring? How did you i=
solate your changes from other variables?=E2=80=9D If you made it up, you=
=E2=80=99ll fumble the answer. And now you=E2=80=99ve lost the job and your=
 credibility.
=E2=9D=8C You set expectations you can=E2=80=99t meet If your portfolio sho=
ws you consistently deliver 20-40% improvements, that=E2=80=99s what the co=
mpany will expect when they hire you. When you can=E2=80=99t deliver (becau=
se those numbers were fiction), you=E2=80=99ve set yourself up to fail.
=E2=9D=8C You miss the chance to show real thinking Honesty about what you =
don=E2=80=99t know is more impressive than fake confidence. =E2=80=9CWe did=
n=E2=80=99t have analytics set up, so I can=E2=80=99t give you hard numbers=
, but here=E2=80=99s the qualitative feedback we got=E2=80=9D shows self-aw=
areness and intellectual honesty.
=E2=9D=8C It reveals you don=E2=80=99t understand how metrics work Saying =
=E2=80=9CI increased revenue by 50%=E2=80=9D without explaining baseline, s=
ample size, timeframe, or confounding variables shows you don=E2=80=99t act=
ually understand measurement. That=E2=80=99s worse than admitting you don=
=E2=80=99t have data.
The truth that hiring managers won=E2=80=99t tell you: They don=E2=80=99t a=
ctually expect junior designers to have perfect metrics on every project. T=
hey know you=E2=80=99re early in your career. They know practice projects e=
xist. What they=E2=80=99re looking for is honest thinking and real problem-=
solving ability.
A case study that says =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t have quantitative data, but=
 here=E2=80=99s what I learned from user feedback=E2=80=9D is infinitely mo=
re valuable than one with fabricated numbers.
How to present real work (even when it=E2=80=99s messy)
Real projects are messy. Constraints are real. You don=E2=80=99t get to do =
everything perfectly. That=E2=80=99s fine. Actually, that=E2=80=99s better =
for your portfolio because it shows you understand how design actually work=
s.
Here=E2=80=99s how to present honest, messy work in a way that still gets y=
ou hired:
1. Be specific about your role (and the team)
Don=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=9CI designed this feature.=E2=80=9D Say exactly wh=
at you did:
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CI was one of two designers on this project. I focused on=
 the mobile experience while Sarah handled desktop. I conducted 6 of the 12=
 user interviews, and we both participated in synthesis.=E2=80=9D
This is honest. It shows collaboration. It shows you understand team dynami=
cs. Hiring managers respect this infinitely more than inflated solo credit.
2. Show the constraints, not just the solution
Every project has limits. Talking about them makes your work more credible:
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CWe had 3 weeks and a developer handoff deadline, so I pr=
ioritized wireframes and basic interactivity testing over high-fidelity moc=
kups. Given more time, I would have tested more variations.=E2=80=9D
This shows you make strategic tradeoffs. That=E2=80=99s a professional skil=
l. Pretending constraints didn=E2=80=99t exist makes you look inexperienced=
=2E
3. Admit what you don=E2=80=99t know or didn=E2=80=99t measure
Honesty about gaps is professional:
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CWe didn=E2=80=99t have analytics instrumentation for thi=
s feature, so I can=E2=80=99t provide conversion metrics. What I do have is=
 usability test feedback from 5 users and support ticket volume before and =
after launch.=E2=80=9D
This shows you understand the difference between quantitative and qualitati=
ve data. It shows you work with what you have. That=E2=80=99s real-world de=
sign.
4. Talk about what didn=E2=80=99t work
Failed experiments are learning opportunities. Show them:
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CMy first concept tested poorly. Users found the navigati=
on confusing. I went back, simplified the structure, and the second round o=
f testing showed significant improvement in task completion.=E2=80=9D
Iteration based on feedback is what design actually is. Showing only succes=
ses makes you look either inexperienced or dishonest.
5. Be honest about practice projects
If it=E2=80=99s a bootcamp project or self-initiated work, just say so. The=
n make it rigorous:
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CThis is a self-initiated project. I identified a real pr=
oblem with my local library=E2=80=99s website by interviewing 5 regular use=
rs. While this didn=E2=80=99t ship, the research and design process are rea=
l.=E2=80=9D
Nobody expects you to only have shipped work if you=E2=80=99re junior. They=
 expect you to demonstrate thinking. Practice projects are fine if you trea=
t them seriously. (Source: Nielsen Norman Group on Portfolios) [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/a597aeb8-6ad9-422a-a016-fd591e618d55?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMWp1ZG=
pwIn0.5o04gUnkd-Msu0Ib_nbCOLc-sw15-DjXlvGx8bWpSeo ]
6. Use qualitative data when you don=E2=80=99t have quantitative
User quotes, feedback themes, observation notes, support ticket reduction, =
stakeholder reactions. These are all valid forms of impact:
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CWhile we didn=E2=80=99t track conversion metrics, we saw=
 support tickets related to checkout drop from ~30/week to ~5/week in the m=
onth after launch.=E2=80=9D
This is real impact, honestly presented.
What to do when you genuinely don=E2=80=99t have metrics
Most junior designers don=E2=80=99t have access to metrics. Many companies =
don=E2=80=99t track things properly. Some projects ship and nobody measures=
 the impact. This is normal. Here=E2=80=99s how to handle it honestly:
Option 1: Explain why metrics don=E2=80=99t exist
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CThis was a client project and I didn=E2=80=99t have acce=
ss to their analytics after handoff.=E2=80=9D =E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CThe compan=
y didn=E2=80=99t have measurement infrastructure in place for this feature.=
=E2=80=9D =E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CThis was exploratory work that informed strate=
gy but didn=E2=80=99t result in a shipped product.=E2=80=9D
These are all legitimate. Just state them matter-of-factly.
Option 2: Use proxy metrics or observations
If you don=E2=80=99t have hard numbers, look for other signals:
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CThe redesigned form reduced the average support call len=
gth from 8 minutes to 3 minutes based on call center reports.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=9C=85 =E2=80=9CUser testing showed task completion time dropped from an av=
erage of 4 minutes to 90 seconds.=E2=80=9D =E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CIn our usabil=
ity tests, 4 out of 5 users completed the task successfully compared to 1 o=
ut of 5 with the old design.=E2=80=9D
These aren=E2=80=99t conversion rates or revenue numbers, but they=E2=80=99=
re real measurements.
Option 3: Focus on the problem-solving process
If you have no outcome data at all, double down on showing your thinking:
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CI can=E2=80=99t measure the impact because the project w=
as paused before launch, but I can walk you through how I identified the co=
re user problem and my rationale for the design decisions.=E2=80=9D
Your thinking process is actually what hiring managers care about most. The=
 metrics are just evidence that the thinking worked. If you have strong thi=
nking, that=E2=80=99s 80% of what matters.
Option 4: Be upfront that it=E2=80=99s a learning project
If it=E2=80=99s bootcamp work or practice:
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CThis is a practice project I completed during my UX boot=
camp. It=E2=80=99s based on research I conducted with real users, but it=E2=
=80=99s not a shipped product.=E2=80=9D
Then show rigorous process. Show real research. Show thoughtful decisions. =
The fact that it didn=E2=80=99t ship is fine if the work is solid.
=F0=9F=8E=AF Take-home: Hiring managers would rather see honest thinking ab=
out a small project than fabricated metrics on a fake one.
The honesty that actually impresses interviewers
Here=E2=80=99s the paradox: the things designers think make them look weak =
are often what actually build credibility.
What you think makes you look bad but actually impresses:
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CI made a mistake in my initial approach=E2=80=9D This sh=
ows self-awareness and learning. Everyone makes mistakes. Acknowledging you=
rs shows maturity.
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t have access to the final metrics=E2=80=
=9D This is honest about real-world constraints. Way better than making num=
bers up.
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CThis was my first time doing [research method] and here=
=E2=80=99s what I learned=E2=80=9D Growth mindset. Willingness to try new t=
hings. Reflective practice. All good signals.
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CThe stakeholder pushed back on my recommendation and we =
had to compromise=E2=80=9D This shows you work with real constraints and co=
llaborate with non-designers. That=E2=80=99s a critical skill.
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CI would do this differently now=E2=80=9D This shows you=
=E2=80=99re growing and learning from experience. Static skills are less va=
luable than learning ability.
=E2=9C=85 =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know, but here=E2=80=99s how I=E2=80=99d=
 figure it out=E2=80=9D In interviews, admitting you don=E2=80=99t know som=
ething and explaining your problem-solving approach is stronger than bullsh=
itting an answer.
What actually makes you look bad:
=E2=9D=8C Taking credit for team work as solo work =E2=9D=8C Fabricating me=
trics you can=E2=80=99t defend =E2=9D=8C Claiming you did research you clea=
rly didn=E2=80=99t do =E2=9D=8C Presenting polished work with no mention of=
 process or iteration =E2=9D=8C Being unable to explain your design decisio=
ns =E2=9D=8C Pretending you have no weaknesses or learning areas
The pattern: Honesty about your actual experience and limitations, combined=
 with clear thinking and genuine learning, beats fabricated perfection ever=
y time.
Hiring managers aren=E2=80=99t looking for designers who never make mistake=
s. They=E2=80=99re looking for designers who think clearly, learn from expe=
rience, and are honest about what they do and don=E2=80=99t know. That=E2=
=80=99s what builds trust. And trust is what gets you hired.
=F0=9F=93=A6 Resource Corner
Honest UX Portfolio Examples (Bestfolios) [ https://substack.com/redirect/c=
e6be27b-2f6d-4c03-b9b4-98314f7b314f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMWp1ZGpwIn0.5o04gUnkd-Msu0I=
b_nbCOLc-sw15-DjXlvGx8bWpSeo ] Browse portfolios that show real work with h=
onest context. Look for ones that mention constraints, team roles, and lear=
ning.
How to Show Process in Your Portfolio (NN/g) [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/8748bee4-30c1-4fae-af7d-16e892692c01?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMWp1ZGpwIn0.5o04gUnkd-Ms=
u0Ib_nbCOLc-sw15-DjXlvGx8bWpSeo ] Research-backed guidance on what to inclu=
de in case studies. Strong on showing thinking over just outcomes.
The Mom Test by Rob Fitzpatrick [ https://substack.com/redirect/20e98920-4a=
99-4868-9362-ac4b2ab36de7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMWp1ZGpwIn0.5o04gUnkd-Msu0Ib_nbCOLc-s=
w15-DjXlvGx8bWpSeo ] While focused on customer interviews, the core lesson =
applies to portfolios: honesty and specificity build more credibility than =
trying to impress.
Case Study Club [ https://substack.com/redirect/cdb0c607-a47a-46a0-b1f3-a2a=
c10dbcab1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMWp1ZGpwIn0.5o04gUnkd-Msu0Ib_nbCOLc-sw15-DjXlvGx8bWpS=
eo ] Collection of case studies with varying levels of polish and honesty. =
Good for seeing different approaches to presenting real work.
Lenny=E2=80=99s Podcast: Portfolio Reviews [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
d456c50d-9e06-4011-ba19-30459a2be551?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMWp1ZGpwIn0.5o04gUnkd-Msu0=
Ib_nbCOLc-sw15-DjXlvGx8bWpSeo ] Occasional episodes where industry leaders =
review portfolios. Listen for what they call out as credible vs questionabl=
e.
Portfolios for UX Researchers (Mixed Methods) [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/0e11ea3a-3129-4ff5-b0b3-b99e64f3b547?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMWp1ZGpwIn0.5o04gUnkd-M=
su0Ib_nbCOLc-sw15-DjXlvGx8bWpSeo ] While focused on research, the advice on=
 presenting rigorous process and being honest about limitations applies to =
design portfolios too.
Redesigning Your Portfolio (A List Apart) [ https://substack.com/redirect/7=
4b39df4-0142-4c15-8425-2dc38239fdc9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMWp1ZGpwIn0.5o04gUnkd-Msu0I=
b_nbCOLc-sw15-DjXlvGx8bWpSeo ] Articles on presenting work honestly and eff=
ectively. Good on the narrative structure of case studies.
Final Thought
Portfolio dishonesty happens because designers are scared. Scared they=E2=
=80=99re not good enough. Scared they don=E2=80=99t have the =E2=80=9Cright=
=E2=80=9D kind of experience. Scared everyone else=E2=80=99s work is better=
=2E So they embellish, exaggerate, or invent to compete.
But here=E2=80=99s what actually happens: the fabrication gets caught, cred=
ibility is destroyed, and the job goes to someone else. Or worse, you get h=
ired based on fake credentials and can=E2=80=99t deliver what you claimed.
The alternative is simpler and more effective: be honest about what you did=
, what you learned, and what you still don=E2=80=99t know. Show real thinki=
ng, even on imperfect projects. Admit constraints. Talk about tradeoffs. Pr=
esent yourself as someone who=E2=80=99s learning and growing, not someone w=
ho=E2=80=99s already perfect.
Hiring managers don=E2=80=99t want perfect designers. Those don=E2=80=99t e=
xist. They want honest ones who can think clearly, learn quickly, and work =
with real-world constraints.
Your real work, honestly presented, is already good enough. Stop lying abou=
t it.
--The UXU Team

