bility;margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 1.16em;fon=
t-size: 1.625em;">The lies hiring managers spot immediately</h2><p style=3D=
"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;=
">Let=E2=80=99s be direct about what=E2=80=99s happening. Designers, especi=
ally junior ones, feel pressure to have impressive portfolios. So they embe=
llish. They exaggerate. Sometimes they straight-up invent things. And hirin=
g managers can tell.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55)=
;line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>Here are the red flags that sc=
ream =E2=80=9Cthis didn=E2=80=99t really happen=E2=80=9D:</strong></p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size:=
 16px;"><span>&#128681; </span><strong>Every project has perfect, round met=
rics</strong><span> =E2=80=9CIncreased conversion by 25%.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=9CReduced bounce rate by 30%.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CImproved user satisfaction=
 by 40%.=E2=80=9D These numbers are suspiciously clean. Real metrics are me=
ssy: 23.7%, 18%, 34.2%. When every project ends in a multiple of 5 or 10, i=
t looks made up.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,=
55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>&#128681; </span><strong>The =
process is too perfect</strong><span> Real design is messy. You interview t=
he wrong people. Stakeholders change their minds. Developers push back on y=
our design. Timeline gets cut. But portfolio case studies show this perfect=
 linear process: research =E2=86=92 insights =E2=86=92 wireframes =E2=86=92=
 testing =E2=86=92 shipping =E2=86=92 success. That=E2=80=99s fiction.</spa=
n></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px=
;font-size: 16px;"><span>&#128681; </span><strong>No mention of constraints=
, tradeoffs, or failures</strong><span> Every real project has constraints.=
 Budget. Timeline. Technical limitations. Stakeholder opinions. But portfol=
io projects never mention them. Every decision was optimal. Nothing was com=
promised. That=E2=80=99s not how work happens.</span></p><p style=3D"margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span=
>&#128681; </span><strong>=E2=80=9CI did everything=E2=80=9D (on a team pro=
ject)</strong><span> =E2=80=9CI conducted the research, designed the soluti=
on, and shipped the feature.=E2=80=9D If this was a real company with a rea=
l team, where was the PM? The researchers? The other designers? Taking sole=
 credit for collaborative work is an instant credibility killer.</span></p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-=
size: 16px;"><span>&#128681; </span><strong>The timeline doesn=E2=80=99t ma=
ke sense</strong><span> =E2=80=9CI conducted 15 user interviews, analyzed t=
he data, created wireframes, built high-fidelity mockups, ran usability tes=
ts, and launched in 2 weeks.=E2=80=9D No, you didn=E2=80=99t. That=E2=80=99=
s 6-8 weeks minimum. Compressed timelines reveal that the story is fabricat=
ed.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-heig=
ht: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>&#128681; </span><strong>Vague or missing =
company/client details</strong><span> =E2=80=9CA fintech startup=E2=80=9D i=
nstead of naming the company. =E2=80=9CAn e-commerce client=E2=80=9D withou=
t specifics. If it was real work, you=E2=80=99d name them (or explain the N=
DA). Vagueness suggests it=E2=80=99s a practice project you=E2=80=99re pret=
ending was real.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,=
55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>&#128681; </span><strong>The =
problems are generic, the solutions are trendy</strong><span> =E2=80=9CUser=
s found the checkout confusing, so I simplified it=E2=80=9D describes every=
 checkout redesign ever. Real projects have specific, messy problems. Gener=
ic problems suggest you=E2=80=99re retrofitting a solution you saw elsewher=
e.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-heigh=
t: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>Why this matters:</strong><span> Hiring m=
anagers aren=E2=80=99t trying to catch you lying. But when they spot incons=
istencies, they start questioning everything in your portfolio. One fabrica=
ted detail ruins your credibility on legitimate work.</span></p><div style=
