e: 16px;"><strong>What actually makes you look bad:</strong></p><p style=3D=
"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;=
">=E2=9D=8C Taking credit for team work as solo work =E2=9D=8C Fabricating =
metrics you can=E2=80=99t defend =E2=9D=8C Claiming you did research you cl=
early didn=E2=80=99t do =E2=9D=8C Presenting polished work with no mention =
of process or iteration =E2=9D=8C Being unable to explain your design decis=
ions =E2=9D=8C Pretending you have no weaknesses or learning areas</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size:=
 16px;"><strong>The pattern:</strong><span> Honesty about your actual exper=
ience and limitations, combined with clear thinking and genuine learning, b=
eats fabricated perfection every time.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Hiring manage=
rs aren=E2=80=99t looking for designers who never make mistakes. They=E2=80=
=99re looking for designers who think clearly, learn from experience, and a=
re honest about what they do and don=E2=80=99t know. That=E2=80=99s what bu=
ilds trust. And trust is what gets you hired.</p><div style=3D"font-size: 1=
