rance: optimizelegibility;-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility;appearance: o=
ptimizelegibility;margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height:=
 1.16em;font-size: 1.625em;">Final Thought</h2><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Portfolio disho=
nesty happens because designers are scared. Scared they=E2=80=99re not good=
 enough. Scared they don=E2=80=99t have the =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D kind of=
 experience. Scared everyone else=E2=80=99s work is better. So they embelli=
sh, exaggerate, or invent to compete.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;col=
or: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">But here=E2=80=99s wh=
at actually happens: the fabrication gets caught, credibility is destroyed,=
 and the job goes to someone else. Or worse, you get hired based on fake cr=
edentials and can=E2=80=99t deliver what you claimed.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">The a=
lternative is simpler and more effective: be honest about what you did, wha=
t you learned, and what you still don=E2=80=99t know. Show real thinking, e=
ven on imperfect projects. Admit constraints. Talk about tradeoffs. Present=
 yourself as someone who=E2=80=99s learning and growing, not someone who=E2=
=80=99s already perfect.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55=
,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Hiring managers don=E2=80=99t want=
 perfect designers. Those don=E2=80=99t exist. They want honest ones who ca=
n think clearly, learn quickly, and work with real-world constraints.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-si=
ze: 16px;">Your real work, honestly presented, is already good enough. Stop=
 lying about it.</p><div style=3D"font-size: 16px;line-height: 26px;"><hr s=
